    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-06-28T21:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-06-28T21:00:00-05:00" n="163"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d163">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">894.8591/2: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-06-29T11:00:00+09:00"
                            >June 29, 1934—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received June 29—12:36 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>137. Department’s instruction No. 517, May 11, 1934.<note n="36"
                        xml:id="d163fn36">Not printed, but see letter of May 11 to the Secretary of
                        the Navy, <ref target="#pg_175">p. 175</ref>.</note> Kobe reports that since
                    March of this year there has been a concentration of more than 400,000 gross
                    tons of Japanese shipping in home waters largely taken from deep-water runs but
                    this is for the most part a normal seasonal trend due to transportation of
                    lumber from the northern islands, carrying supplies to the fishing fleets, et
                    cetera. The new large and fast motor freighters are still on deep-sea runs.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
